:::summary
Einstein's theory of relativity — encompassing both special relativity (1905) and general relativity (1915) — fundamentally transformed our understanding of space, time, mass, energy, and gravity. Special relativity showed that the speed of light is constant for all observers and that space and time are interwoven into a single fabric. General relativity extended these ideas to gravity, describing it as the curvature of space-time caused by mass and energy. Together they form the bedrock of modern cosmology and astrophysics.
:::

